Explose-- explosives,
they knock things apart.

00:25:20.350 --> 00:25:26.480 align:middle line:84%
But you can also destruct--
destruct material, buildings,

00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:28.080 align:middle line:90%
armor by means of heat.

00:25:28.080 --> 00:25:30.420 align:middle line:84%
That is, you're bringing
in a charge which

00:25:30.420 --> 00:25:32.920 align:middle line:84%
is-- eventually is so
hot that you simply

00:25:32.920 --> 00:25:34.240 align:middle line:90%
burn your way through it.

00:25:34.240 --> 00:25:36.540 align:middle line:84%
This is called an
incendiary, and it's

00:25:36.540 --> 00:25:41.600 align:middle line:84%
based on a chemical reaction
called the thermite reaction.

00:25:41.600 --> 00:25:45.080 align:middle line:84%
Steven E. Jones--
everybody who has

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:48.420 align:middle line:84%
seen the collapse
of the Twin Towers

00:25:48.420 --> 00:25:51.690 align:middle line:84%
and eventually, if
they are informed,

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:54.590 align:middle line:84%
also the collapse
of Building Seven

00:25:54.590 --> 00:25:58.590 align:middle line:84%
observe that these
collapses was accompanied

00:25:58.590 --> 00:26:02.260 align:middle line:90%
by huge dust clouds.

00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:04.840 align:middle line:84%
And that-- actually, that's
another observation which

00:26:04.840 --> 00:26:08.570 align:middle line:84%
points to controlled
demolition, because these dust

00:26:08.570 --> 00:26:16.110 align:middle line:84%
clouds expand in a fashion which
you only see from volcanoes.

00:26:16.110 --> 00:26:18.060 align:middle line:90%
It was not ordinary dust clouds.

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:20.040 align:middle line:90%
They were burning hot.

00:26:20.040 --> 00:26:22.330 align:middle line:84%
People were actually
getting burns

00:26:22.330 --> 00:26:24.810 align:middle line:84%
from being exposed
to these dust clouds,

00:26:24.810 --> 00:26:30.290 align:middle line:84%
meaning that there is something
very special going on here.

00:26:30.290 --> 00:26:33.720 align:middle line:84%
Everything was pulverized
from all three skyscrapers

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:35.480 align:middle line:90%
except for the steel.

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:37.150 align:middle line:84%
Everything was
turned into-- now,

00:26:37.150 --> 00:26:40.650 align:middle line:84%
the first responders
and the cleanup workers,

00:26:40.650 --> 00:26:43.390 align:middle line:84%
they reported that
the biggest chunk I--

00:26:43.390 --> 00:26:49.350 align:middle line:84%
I've-- I've found was-- was
the keyboard of a telephone.

00:26:49.350 --> 00:26:50.970 align:middle line:90%
Everything was pulverized.

00:26:50.970 --> 00:26:54.170 align:middle line:84%
Also, the remains of
human beings-- they

00:26:54.170 --> 00:26:56.060 align:middle line:90%
were absolutely nothing left.

00:26:56.060 --> 00:27:02.290 align:middle line:84%
They were finding tiny, tiny
fractures of human bones

00:27:02.290 --> 00:27:07.200 align:middle line:84%
on the roofs of-- of-- of--
of the neighboring buildings.

00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:09.280 align:middle line:84%
On the rooftops
of Deutsche Bank,

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:14.750 align:middle line:84%
actually many years later, they
found fractured bone fragments.

00:27:14.750 --> 00:27:19.150 align:middle line:84%
So meaning, this
alone, I'm just--

00:27:19.150 --> 00:27:20.600 align:middle line:90%
there's so many observations.

00:27:20.600 --> 00:27:23.400 align:middle line:84%
This alone means that
these poor people

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:29.170 align:middle line:84%
were not caught by the falling
masses of the building.

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:31.790 align:middle line:90%
They would blown apart.

00:27:31.790 --> 00:27:35.350 align:middle line:84%
So everything,
including the people,

00:27:35.350 --> 00:27:37.890 align:middle line:90%
were completely pulverized.

00:27:37.890 --> 00:27:40.840 align:middle line:84%
So there were
hundreds of thousands

00:27:40.840 --> 00:27:43.820 align:middle line:84%
of tons of what we
call World Trade

00:27:43.820 --> 00:27:50.500 align:middle line:84%
Center dust sprayed all over the
southern Manhattan on that day.

00:27:50.500 --> 00:27:52.410 align:middle line:90%
Everything.

00:27:52.410 --> 00:27:56.280 align:middle line:84%
And this dust was
characterized very

00:27:56.280 --> 00:27:58.860 align:middle line:84%
early on, actually,
by a private company

00:27:58.860 --> 00:28:00.700 align:middle line:90%
called the RJ Lee Group.

00:28:00.700 --> 00:28:04.940 align:middle line:84%
And their report-- first
report came out in 2003,

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:07.490 align:middle line:90%
another report in 2004.

00:28:07.490 --> 00:28:10.540 align:middle line:84%
United States Geological
Survey in California,

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:13.330 align:middle line:84%
they came out also
with a characterization

00:28:13.330 --> 00:28:15.420 align:middle line:90%
of the dust in 2005.

00:28:15.420 --> 00:28:20.260 align:middle line:84%
And from these reports--
Steven E. Jones,

00:28:20.260 --> 00:28:23.820 align:middle line:84%
I just mentioned him,
looked into these reports.

00:28:23.820 --> 00:28:28.180 align:middle line:84%
And there were some observations
which was just outrageous.

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:32.020 align:middle line:84%
And in some pointed to
the-- to the occurrence

00:28:32.020 --> 00:28:35.420 align:middle line:84%
of extremely high temperatures
during the collapses

00:28:35.420 --> 00:28:36.750 align:middle line:90%
of this building.

00:28:36.750 --> 00:28:41.700 align:middle line:84%
Among other things, you
find-- you find in the dust

00:28:41.700 --> 00:28:48.590 align:middle line:84%
some very tiny, completely
round spheres of iron.

00:28:48.590 --> 00:28:52.280 align:middle line:84%
You don't find this in
ordinary building dust.

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:54.470 align:middle line:84%
And this points
to the application

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:58.050 align:middle line:84%
of thermite which I've just
explained and mentioned.

00:28:58.050 --> 00:29:01.530 align:middle line:84%
And what-- and
other observations

00:29:01.530 --> 00:29:03.940 align:middle line:90%
pointing in the same direction.

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:08.040 align:middle line:84%
But the short and long
story is that Jones,

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:12.200 align:middle line:84%
in late 2006 that
we have to look

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:14.170 align:middle line:90%
into-- further into the dust.

00:29:14.170 --> 00:29:18.370 align:middle line:84%
Because maybe there's
something left.

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:23.390 align:middle line:84%
When you have explosions or
when you apply incendiaries,

00:29:23.390 --> 00:29:25.640 align:middle line:90%
the reaction is never complete.

00:29:25.640 --> 00:29:27.290 align:middle line:90%
There's always something left.

00:29:27.290 --> 00:29:33.600 align:middle line:84%
If you have an act of terrorism
or whenever people are using

00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:39.540 align:middle line:84%
explosives, the police come to
the crime site and they can--

00:29:39.540 --> 00:29:41.090 align:middle line:84%
they can-- there are
always something left.

00:29:41.090 --> 00:29:44.970 align:middle line:84%
They can identify what
kind of explosive was used.

00:29:44.970 --> 00:29:46.850 align:middle line:84%
So Jones speculated
maybe there's

00:29:46.850 --> 00:29:49.310 align:middle line:84%
some unreactive thermite
left, so he took

00:29:49.310 --> 00:29:50.900 align:middle line:90%
a closer look into the dust.

00:29:50.900 --> 00:29:54.530 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, he found, what
we call, red-gray chips.

00:29:54.530 --> 00:29:56.630 align:middle line:84%
Now, I'm using-- I'm
holding up my finger here,

00:29:56.630 --> 00:30:00.780 align:middle line:84%
but the fact is, most of them--
they're less than a millimeter.

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:03.460 align:middle line:84%
You need a microscope,
actually, to see them.

00:30:03.460 --> 00:30:05.760 align:middle line:84%
And also, you need a
magnet, because they

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:08.370 align:middle line:90%
are attracted by-- by a magnet.

00:30:08.370 --> 00:30:11.280 align:middle line:84%
So what you do, you apply
a magnet to the dust.

00:30:11.280 --> 00:30:12.980 align:middle line:90%
You get out something.

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:17.010 align:middle line:84%
Of course, what you get out are
also these small iron spheres.

00:30:17.010 --> 00:30:18.280 align:middle line:90%
They're magnetic.

00:30:18.280 --> 00:30:23.100 align:middle line:84%
But with them also, eventually,
if you look under a microscope,

00:30:23.100 --> 00:30:26.800 align:middle line:90%
you see these small chips.

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:30.010 align:middle line:84%
Then there was a form--
a team of scientists

00:30:30.010 --> 00:30:31.660 align:middle line:90%
to investigate these chips.

00:30:31.660 --> 00:30:36.560 align:middle line:84%
I was invited to join this
team and was on board,

00:30:36.560 --> 00:30:40.670 align:middle line:84%
not on the initial findings
which was done by Jones alone,

00:30:40.670 --> 00:30:43.700 align:middle line:84%
but by-- in the characterization
and the investigation

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:45.150 align:middle line:90%
of these chips.

00:30:45.150 --> 00:30:47.410 align:middle line:84%
It led to a
scientific publication

00:30:47.410 --> 00:30:49.940 align:middle line:90%
which came out in April 2009.

00:30:49.940 --> 00:30:57.710 align:middle line:84%
And the main conclusion here
is that these chips are-- were

00:30:57.710 --> 00:31:01.760 align:middle line:84%
unreacted thermitic
material, that is,

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:05.540 align:middle line:84%
when you take it
and-- and heat it up.

00:31:05.540 --> 00:31:07.930 align:middle line:84%
At some point, at
some temperature, 430

00:31:07.930 --> 00:31:11.310 align:middle line:90%
degrees centigrade, it reacts.

00:31:11.310 --> 00:31:16.760 align:middle line:84%
And it forms the same iron
spheres which has been found

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:22.460 align:middle line:90%
in abundance in the bulk dust.

00:31:22.460 --> 00:31:23.280 align:middle line:90%
And that's it.

00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:27.220 align:middle line:84%
So this is unreactive
thermitic material.

00:31:27.220 --> 00:31:32.330 align:middle line:84%
And I use this very
vague term intentionally,

00:31:32.330 --> 00:31:34.690 align:middle line:84%
because there's been a
lot of misunderstanding,

00:31:34.690 --> 00:31:37.720 align:middle line:90%
actually, about this finding.

00:31:37.720 --> 00:31:41.080 align:middle line:84%
I told you that we know that
incindiaries were used--

00:31:41.080 --> 00:31:43.060 align:middle line:84%
we know that the
thermite has been used

00:31:43.060 --> 00:31:46.770 align:middle line:90%
for cutting the steel beams.

00:31:46.770 --> 00:31:49.260 align:middle line:84%
Maybe not the red-gray
chips material.

00:31:49.260 --> 00:31:51.570 align:middle line:90%
Actually, I don't believe it.

00:31:51.570 --> 00:31:54.740 align:middle line:84%
And we also know that
explosives were used.

00:31:54.740 --> 00:32:01.580 align:middle line:84%
And the confusion comes in
because what we are talking

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:05.340 align:middle line:84%
about here is what,
in a broad term

00:32:05.340 --> 00:32:10.250 align:middle line:84%
is called energetic materials,
and the thermite reaction

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:14.210 align:middle line:90%
has a lot of energy in it.

00:32:14.210 --> 00:32:16.980 align:middle line:90%
But it's-- it is slow.

00:32:16.980 --> 00:32:23.480 align:middle line:84%
Explosives are not-- are
not particularly energetic.

00:32:23.480 --> 00:32:26.420 align:middle line:84%
People-- many people
might think that you have

00:32:26.420 --> 00:32:28.600 align:middle line:90%
a lot of energy in explosives.

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:29.300 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:32:29.300 --> 00:32:35.150 align:middle line:84%
The point about explosives is
that their reaction is so fast.

00:32:35.150 --> 00:32:37.095 align:middle line:90%
It's very, very quick.

00:32:37.095 --> 00:32:39.730 align:middle line:84%
So-- and you develop
a gas super fast.

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:44.320 align:middle line:84%
That's why you have
the explosion effect.

00:32:44.320 --> 00:32:46.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:50.770 align:middle line:84%
So in the early 90s
research started

00:32:50.770 --> 00:32:55.450 align:middle line:84%
to try to get the
chemical energy

00:32:55.450 --> 00:33:02.740 align:middle line:84%
from the thermite reaction and
convert it into an explosive.

00:33:02.740 --> 00:33:08.310 align:middle line:84%
And this is-- this is the
emergence of nanotechnology

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:12.390 align:middle line:84%
which is a phrase which most
people have heard of at least.

00:33:12.390 --> 00:33:18.740 align:middle line:84%
The point here being is that
you can bring particles.

00:33:18.740 --> 00:33:22.560 align:middle line:84%
You can make them so small that
you are actually approaching

00:33:22.560 --> 00:33:26.220 align:middle line:84%
molecular dimensions, meaning
that if you have two reactants

00:33:26.220 --> 00:33:28.950 align:middle line:84%
who have to react, when
the particles are so small,

00:33:28.950 --> 00:33:33.690 align:middle line:84%
you can get them much
more intimately mixed.

00:33:33.690 --> 00:33:37.340 align:middle line:84%
So now, you can have the
thermite reaction running

00:33:37.340 --> 00:33:39.670 align:middle line:90%
as fast as an explosive.

00:33:39.670 --> 00:33:44.020 align:middle line:84%
And if you then add other
chemicals to the material,

00:33:44.020 --> 00:33:46.980 align:middle line:84%
you can produce a
gas, meaning that you

00:33:46.980 --> 00:33:51.980 align:middle line:84%
are getting the best of two
worlds in modern explosives.

00:33:51.980 --> 00:33:53.330 align:middle line:84%
You're getting the
best of two worlds.

00:33:53.330 --> 00:33:56.360 align:middle line:84%
You're getting the energy
from the thermite reaction

00:33:56.360 --> 00:33:58.255 align:middle line:84%
and-- but it's running
so fast that you

00:33:58.255 --> 00:33:59.860 align:middle line:90%
are making an explosive.

00:33:59.860 --> 00:34:07.520 align:middle line:84%
So the principle of the thermite
reaction, and we know this,

00:34:07.520 --> 00:34:12.080 align:middle line:84%
can be applied for
developing explosives.

00:34:12.080 --> 00:34:15.530 align:middle line:84%
And just the other day,
actually two weeks ago,

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:21.699 align:middle line:84%
we found a patent from 1993
from Lawrence Livermore National

00:34:21.699 --> 00:34:27.340 align:middle line:84%
Laboratory whether actually
patenting explosives based

00:34:27.340 --> 00:34:29.969 align:middle line:84%
on this technology-- not
exactly the same thing

00:34:29.969 --> 00:34:31.819 align:middle line:84%
as we found in the
red-gray chips.

00:34:31.819 --> 00:34:34.639 align:middle line:84%
The point being, and
that's the only point,

00:34:34.639 --> 00:34:41.449 align:middle line:84%
is that the thermite reaction
can be used for developing

00:34:41.449 --> 00:34:45.600 align:middle line:84%
explosives, but we
do not know actually

00:34:45.600 --> 00:34:49.969 align:middle line:84%
what kind of explosives were
used in World Trade Center.

00:34:49.969 --> 00:34:51.020 align:middle line:90%
We don't know.

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:54.469 align:middle line:84%
LILOU MACE: But idea of it
being caused by the plane

00:34:54.469 --> 00:34:58.700 align:middle line:84%
and-- is totally,
totally absurd to you.

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:01.220 align:middle line:10%
NIELS HARRIT:
That's totally out.

00:35:01.220 --> 00:35:04.590 align:middle line:10%
I-- I consider on
that conclusion,

00:35:04.590 --> 00:35:08.120 align:middle line:10%
I consider scientific
mainstream.

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:11.500 align:middle line:84%
The only problem is that
nobody dares to talk about it,

00:35:11.500 --> 00:35:14.120 align:middle line:84%
because it is a
very, very bad career

00:35:14.120 --> 00:35:20.970 align:middle line:84%
move at all at a university
to-- to raise these questions.

00:35:20.970 --> 00:35:24.660 align:middle line:84%
All American universities
are dependent on government

00:35:24.660 --> 00:35:25.820 align:middle line:90%
funding.

00:35:25.820 --> 00:35:27.940 align:middle line:84%
You don't talk
about these things,

00:35:27.940 --> 00:35:31.688 align:middle line:90%
not even at the lunch table.

00:35:31.688 --> 00:35:35.760 align:middle line:10%
And Stephen Jones was
forced, actually-- he was

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:38.570 align:middle line:10%
forced into early retirement.

00:35:38.570 --> 00:35:40.560 align:middle line:90%
Not kicked out.

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:43.140 align:middle line:90%
I think he struck a fair deal.

00:35:43.140 --> 00:35:46.570 align:middle line:84%
And I must say-- I must
say that Brigham Young

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:53.630 align:middle line:84%
University, actually,
in the course of events

00:35:53.630 --> 00:35:55.710 align:middle line:90%
were not unfair.

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:59.510 align:middle line:84%
Because we had access to
all the equipment there,

00:35:59.510 --> 00:36:02.700 align:middle line:84%
and they had a
beautiful microscope.

00:36:02.700 --> 00:36:05.340 align:middle line:84%
This-- now I'm talking-- I'm
talking about instruments

00:36:05.340 --> 00:36:06.227 align:middle line:90%
which is of course--

00:36:06.227 --> 00:36:07.659 align:middle line:84%
LILOU MACE: Your toys.
NIELS HARRIT: Yeah.

00:36:07.659 --> 00:36:10.890 align:middle line:84%
Which is-- which is-- which
is actually decisive for--for

00:36:10.890 --> 00:36:12.240 align:middle line:90%
doing this kind of research.

00:36:12.240 --> 00:36:15.250 align:middle line:84%
And now we have a good
instrument at Copenhagen,

00:36:15.250 --> 00:36:16.660 align:middle line:90%
but at that time we didn't.

00:36:16.660 --> 00:36:20.360 align:middle line:84%
But the instrument at that time
which they had at Brigham Young

00:36:20.360 --> 00:36:25.310 align:middle line:84%
was very good and a very
good man operating it.

00:36:25.310 --> 00:36:27.660 align:middle line:90%
And he's still there.

00:36:27.660 --> 00:36:30.920 align:middle line:84%
So-- so actually, so Jones
had access to the equipment.

00:36:30.920 --> 00:36:32.680 align:middle line:90%
It was done on Brigham Young.

00:36:32.680 --> 00:36:35.840 align:middle line:84%
They actually had
the opportunity

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:41.910 align:middle line:84%
to read our publication
prior to submission.

00:36:41.910 --> 00:36:44.580 align:middle line:90%
So they got the final word.

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:51.040 align:middle line:84%
And-- and-- and they also
came with some reservations

00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:54.000 align:middle line:84%
which I actually was
quite happy about.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:56.730 align:middle line:90%


00:36:56.730 --> 00:37:00.280 align:middle line:84%
Because there were nine
authors on this--on this paper.

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:04.160 align:middle line:84%
And you may imagine
one guy's in Australia,

00:37:04.160 --> 00:37:05.850 align:middle line:84%
and I'm sitting in
Copenhagen. There

00:37:05.850 --> 00:37:08.790 align:middle line:84%
was a lot of discussion
going back and forth

00:37:08.790 --> 00:37:11.940 align:middle line:90%
when we were writing it up.

00:37:11.940 --> 00:37:16.850 align:middle line:84%
And some of the other
guys were more--

00:37:16.850 --> 00:37:24.525 align:middle line:84%
wanted to, what should I say,
point more to the implications

00:37:24.525 --> 00:37:25.640 align:middle line:90%
of our findings.

00:37:25.640 --> 00:37:31.980 align:middle line:84%
And I was-- I wanted it to--
should be strictly scientific.

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:35.035 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we should just
tell about our findings,

00:37:35.035 --> 00:37:36.730 align:middle line:90%
our conclusions, and that's it.

00:37:36.730 --> 00:37:39.500 align:middle line:84%
And that's about
roughly the same

00:37:39.500 --> 00:37:43.900 align:middle line:90%
as Brigham Young asked us to do.

00:37:43.900 --> 00:37:45.610 align:middle line:90%
Just to report the facts.

00:37:45.610 --> 00:37:49.450 align:middle line:84%
So I was actually
happy with what--

00:37:49.450 --> 00:37:54.520 align:middle line:90%
with this-- with Brigham Young.

00:37:54.520 --> 00:37:56.520 align:middle line:90%
They were fair.

00:37:56.520 --> 00:37:58.090 align:middle line:90%
There were fair.

00:37:58.090 --> 00:38:01.890 align:middle line:84%
I certainly understand
the problems

00:38:01.890 --> 00:38:06.200 align:middle line:84%
of any academic institution
in the United States

00:38:06.200 --> 00:38:10.250 align:middle line:84%
or in Denmark or anywhere in the
Western hemisphere, actually,

